[
    {
        "content": "<p>There is a well known equivalence between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span></span></span></span>-principal bundles and locally free sheaves. Lots of people are very interested in (co)chain complexes of the latter, but google shows zero results for \"complex of (G-)principal bundles\". Do people not study complexes of principal bundles?</p>",
        "id": 213704244,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603024023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I can believe that there is an equivalence between the <em>groupoid</em> of locally free sheaves and the groupoid of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">GL</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>-principal bundles, but not between the corresponding categories. Or do I misunderstand?</p>",
        "id": 213709489,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1603032444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I think this is right.</p>",
        "id": 213709555,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1603032488
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, I think the original statement is lacking an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> in a couple places, but maybe there's a version of it which doesn't need one (involving a principal bundle for a groupoid?)</p>",
        "id": 213709641,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1603032611
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What would a complex of principal bundles even be?   A chain complex is a bunch of objects with maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d_i : C_i \\to C_{i+1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.84444em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.891661em;vertical-align:-0.208331em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.311664em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.208331em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> s.t. that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d_{i+1} d_i = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.902771em;vertical-align:-0.208331em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.311664em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.208331em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>.    For this \"0\" to make sense we at least need the hom-sets to be pointed sets, though typically go much further and demand that our category be enriched over abelian groups.   The category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-principal bundles for fixed <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> doesn't have these properties, so <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d_{i+1} d_i = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.902771em;vertical-align:-0.208331em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.311664em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.208331em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> doesn't make sense for these.</p>",
        "id": 213715837,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603041267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As Todd+Reid pointed out, the \"equivalence between locally free sheaves and GL-principal bundles\" is really an equivalence between the groupoid of locally free sheaves of vector spaces of rank n and the groupoid of GL(n)-principal bundles.</p>",
        "id": 213715932,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603041393
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In neither of these groupoids do chain complexes make sense.</p>",
        "id": 213716041,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603041548
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course we can formally get rid of the dependence on n by taking the \"union\" (coproduct) of all these groupoids, but that doesn't help make sense of chain complexes.</p>",
        "id": 213716063,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603041588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We can define chain complexes in the category of locally free sheaves of vector spaces.</p>",
        "id": 213716125,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603041644
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In much less fancy term: chain complexes live in the world of linear algebra, but principal bundles don't.</p>",
        "id": 213716984,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603042947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hm, I must admit, I've only ever thought of (locally free sheaves &lt;-&gt; principal bundles) as a naïve algebraic geometer, and just how to turn one object into the other — I'd never stopped to think whether or not this association gave something on the level of morphisms</p>",
        "id": 213717540,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603043839
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so is there no functor from the category of locally free sheaves (of some fixed rank <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>) to the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-principal bundles such that it acts on objects by sending a locally free sheaf to the associated principal bundle?</p>",
        "id": 213717591,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603043898
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(or vice versa, I guess)</p>",
        "id": 213717595,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603043904
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What \"category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-principal bundles\" are you talking about?    There really aren't interesting morphisms between principal G-bundles other than isomorphisms... in general.</p>",
        "id": 213717628,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603043988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a functor from the <em>groupoid</em> of principal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-bundles to the <em>groupoid</em> of rank-n locally free sheaves, and this is an equivalence.</p>",
        "id": 213717702,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603044080
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then there's an inclusion of the groupoid of rank-n locally free sheaves into the <em>category</em> of rank-n locally free sheaves.</p>",
        "id": 213717762,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603044153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you can create a category of principal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-bundles by taking the groupoid of these and throwing in extra morphisms that are secretly morphisms between their associated rank-n locally free sheaves.   You get a category equivalent to the category of rank-n locally free sheaves.  </p>\n<p>But this is a rather roundabout way of saying \"forget principal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-bundles: I'd rather work with rank-n locally free sheaves\".</p>",
        "id": 213717876,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603044310
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/241590-theory.3A-algebraic.20topology.20.26.20homological.20algebra/topic/complexes.20of.20bundles/near/213717628\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>What \"category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-principal bundles\" are you talking about?    There really aren't interesting morphisms between principal G-bundles other than isomorphisms... in general.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>this explains why I've never read anything about morphisms between principal bundles then! you've piqued my interest with your \"...  in general\" though — what sort of secrets are you hiding there? <span aria-label=\"wink\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f609\" role=\"img\" title=\"wink\">:wink:</span></p>",
        "id": 213723384,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603051932
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, I later explained a way you can \"cook up\" a concept of morphism between principal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{GL}_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> bundles.</p>",
        "id": 213723508,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603052098
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, yes, and this seems quite nice to me, but I get that you might as well just work with locally free sheaves at this point... but I'm still interested in this category anyway! is it studied somewhere at all?</p>",
        "id": 213723598,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1603052237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Btw, the automorphisms of a principal G-bundle can still be interesting.   For example consider the trivial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{U}(1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">U</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-bundle on the circle, or the trivial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}^\\ast</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> bundle if you prefer.  I think this has some automorphisms that aren't homotopic to the identity...</p>",
        "id": 213723753,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603052426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280178\">Tim Hosgood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/241590-theory.3A-algebraic.20topology.20.26.20homological.20algebra/topic/complexes.20of.20bundles/near/213723598\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>OK, yes, and this seems quite nice to me, but I get that you might as well just work with locally free sheaves at this point... but I'm still interested in this category anyway! is it studied somewhere at all?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The category of locally free sheaves has been studied a lot.  I doubt anyone has bothered to study this other equivalent category - I just made it up to please you.   But all \"non-evil\" results about the category of locally free sheaves results will automatically transfer to this equivalent category.</p>",
        "id": 213723848,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603052566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There is a Tannakian interpretation of principal bundles (and of connections and Higgs fields on them) as strict exact faithful tensor functors from Rep(G) to Vect(X) due to Nori and Simpson, which is kind of related to this discussion. I am on my phone so I can't really go into details, and I will just refer to section 9 of Simpson's \"Moduli of representations of the fundamental group of a smooth projective variety II\" (<a href=\"http://www.numdam.org/article/PMIHES_1994__80__5_0.pdf\">http://www.numdam.org/article/PMIHES_1994__80__5_0.pdf</a>)</p>",
        "id": 221021484,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Pepin Lehalleur",
        "timestamp": 1609099988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's an old discussion so maybe you won't see this? I will tag just in case: <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280178\">@Tim Hosgood</span>   <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span></p>",
